WEBVTT

1.1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.761
It looks like a stone.

1.2
00:00:03.761 --> 00:00:07.523
But it does not behave like a regular stone.

1.3
00:00:07.523 --> 00:00:11.284
This is SilverStone — and this module makes you fluent in it.

2.1
00:00:11.284 --> 00:00:16.009
SilverStone is our patented wellness stone.

2.2
00:00:16.009 --> 00:00:20.734
We take porcelain clay, heat it to thirteen hundred degrees Celsius, and infuse it with silver and copper nano-particles.

2.3
00:00:20.734 --> 00:00:25.459
That makes it anti-bacterial, non-porous, stain-proof, scratch-resistant, and impact-resistant.

2.4
00:00:25.459 --> 00:00:30.185
It's one hundred percent food-grade — you can eat directly off it.

2.5
00:00:30.185 --> 00:00:34.910
Stronger than granite.

2.6
00:00:34.910 --> 00:00:39.635
More elegant than marble.

2.7
00:00:39.635 --> 00:00:44.360
Engineered, not mined.

3.1
00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:48.434
Present the seven safety pillars in this order, every time.

3.2
00:00:48.434 --> 00:00:52.509
Stain safe.

3.3
00:00:52.509 --> 00:00:56.584
Scratch safe.

3.4
00:00:56.584 --> 00:01:00.658
High load bearing — drawers hold up to sixty kilos each.

3.5
00:01:00.658 --> 00:01:04.733
Fire safe.

3.6
00:01:04.733 --> 00:01:08.807
Water safe — in a thirty-day water test, wood swelled while the stone stayed unchanged.

3.7
00:01:08.807 --> 00:01:12.882
Impact safe — a heavy ceramic jar dropped on it left it intact.

3.8
00:01:12.882 --> 00:01:16.956
And more storage — up to sixty-two percent more than standard kitchens.

4.1
00:01:16.956 --> 00:01:22.183
Granite is porous — it absorbs stains and bacteria and needs polishing.

4.2
00:01:22.183 --> 00:01:27.410
Marble comes from mining and needs constant care.

4.3
00:01:27.410 --> 00:01:32.637
Tiles trap dirt and fungus in their grout lines.

4.4
00:01:32.637 --> 00:01:37.864
SilverStone is non-porous, antibacterial, uniform — with no grout lines at all.

5.1
00:01:37.864 --> 00:01:45.481
And the big one — compressed wood.

5.2
00:01:45.481 --> 00:01:53.099
The material costs under one hundred rupees a square foot and brings formaldehyde, termites, and moisture damage.

5.3
00:01:53.099 --> 00:02:00.716
SilverStone material is around five hundred rupees a square foot — antibacterial, termite-proof, maintenance-free — at a similar finished kitchen price.

6.1
00:02:00.716 --> 00:02:04.858
Know these cold.

6.2
00:02:04.858 --> 00:02:09.001
The cabinet structure balances the stone's weight — no impact on flooring.

6.3
00:02:09.001 --> 00:02:13.143
It won't warp, bend, or sag.

6.4
00:02:13.143 --> 00:02:17.285
The hardware is patented, built in the same European facilities as Blum and Grass, carries over a hundred kilos, and is rust-resistant with a ten-year warranty.

6.5
00:02:17.285 --> 00:02:21.427
And maintenance?

6.6
00:02:21.427 --> 00:02:25.570
A damp cloth.

6.7
00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:29.712
Nothing else, ever.

7.1
00:02:29.712 --> 00:02:34.853
Your notes for this module.

7.2
00:02:34.853 --> 00:02:39.993
One — porcelain clay, thirteen hundred degrees, silver and copper nano-particles.

7.3
00:02:39.993 --> 00:02:45.134
Two — seven safety pillars, always in order; drawers hold sixty kilos; up to sixty-two percent more storage.

7.4
00:02:45.134 --> 00:02:50.275
Three — non-porous and one hundred percent food-grade: you can eat directly off it.

7.5
00:02:50.275 --> 00:02:55.415
Four — maintenance is a damp cloth.

7.6
00:02:55.415 --> 00:03:00.556
No polishing, ever.

8.1
00:03:00.556 --> 00:03:05.154
Stronger than granite, more elegant than marble, safer than wood.

8.2
00:03:05.154 --> 00:03:09.752
Now prove it — take the quiz.

